The paper discusses the use of information-theoretic measures, such as entropy, in estimating the complexity of graphs. This topic falls under the intersection of several CS subfields, including information theory (cs.IT), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper's focus on graph theory and information theory suggests that cs.IT and cs.DM are the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.DS and cs.CC due to the discussion of graph constructions and computable measures. The mention of causal likelihood also suggests a connection to machine learning, hence cs.LG is a possible sub-category as well.
